items have no fixed points value, if you want it you bid on it.<br>
if someone bids higher than you, you can go higher as well.<br>
min bid is 5 points, raise is 5 as well unless you hit your max value<br>
(say you have 92 points, other person says 90, you'd have to say 95 but can't, so you're allowed to say 92. next bid has to be 95.)<br>
you pay for an item with how much time it's worth to you. fun to watch at times <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=592"><img src="http://ronaan.homestead.com/files/RonaanSig.gif"/</a><br><a href="http://www.wolfsclan-eq.de">Transcendent of Wolfsclan</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=meniafimbulstochter>Menia Fimbulstochter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/5/03 8:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1958.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: old school</span><hr size=1> We use a mixed system of Raidpoints and Lotto.<br>
<br>
You get Points by attending a raids, as normal. Every Item has a base value. The Points are used to bid on items as well as to cover the base costs. If an item drops which several people want, they bid points (in tell) to the &quot;lootmaster&quot;. Then, they add the points they bid to their rolls. You can chose not to bid points and just roll as well.<br>
<br>
Example: Player A wants an item really bad, bids 400 points and thus rolls 400 to 500.<br>
Player B would like the item as well, had only 200 points, which he used, so rolls 200 to 300.<br>
Player C would lik the item but is actually saving for another one but gives it a try and rolls 0 to 100.<br>
<br>
Obviously, Player A's roll can't be bested, anyway, so he gets the item, pays 400 points + Base Item cost.<br>
<br>
This way, loot still gets to the one who really spends a bunch of points, but gives people a fair chance to get items even if they weren't able to amass ungodly amounts of raidpoints. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://hseipp.bei.t-online.de/Menia-2-longtext.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zukobim>Zukobim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/5/03 9:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1958.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: old school</span><hr size=1> My guild is not a raid guild, but we raid alot.<br>
Our raidpoint-system (RP) has bonus for signing up in a set time before the raid, bonus per hour attended, bonus for being their when the raid ends and kill-bonus for certain named mobs.<br>
The system also has penalties for signing up, but being late or not attending at all without noticing the RL in time.<br>
Only the RL get a little extra RP-bonus for his job.<br>
<br>
It sounds a bit complicated, but we use a few standardized commands in a specific chat channel, like (START), (KILL) &lt;mob&gt;, (LOOT) &lt;item&gt; &lt;player&gt; and so on.<br>
The log will then be uploaded through a web-interface and parsed.<br>
All data about attendence, loot and so on are then stored in a database with several different options for data-extraction.<br>
<br>
All items has a fixed value from a huge list made by our loot-council (LC).<br>
When a player wants an item, then he simply say &quot;INT&quot; in the raid channel and the RL or some loot-manager, then gather all the interested players and make a fast lookup of RP either through our web-interface or by using our IRC-bot.<br>
The player that has the most RP gets the item and the item value is then deducted from his RP-account.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thedrunkenmage>The Drunken Mage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/5/03 1:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1958.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: old school</span><hr size=1> My guild uses a point system.<br>
<br>
Every item that drops has a point value.  If you have enough points for the item, you can go in for it on a lotto.<br>
<br>
We also have &quot;tiers.&quot;  Basically they are point levels at which you get a second, third, or fourth number (chance) in the lotto.  This removes a little bit of the &quot;luck&quot; involved and gives people who have been saving their points for a long time a better shot at items (without allowing them to essentially get it defaulted by being able to outbid everyone else).<br>
<br>
Points in = points out.  If 20 points of loot drops on a raid, and there are 40 people present... everyone earns 0.5 points for the raid.<br>
<br>
It's fairly easy to administer (thanks to some tools that were developed by our code monkeys) and it does a good job of providing an even loot distribution (assuming equal attendance). <p><table border="0" width="568">
