<br>
When you progress past that to the point where you are in the &quot;gearing up&quot; phase of a guilds life - hitting raid zones like an old world plane, Kael Arena, Halls of Testing to gear your guild up to start on targets like Vindi, WToV named etc then officer assigned loot works best.  The players who play the most will get the most loot, your active tanks get kitted out quickly as neccessary for moving up the ladder.<br>
<br>
Once you are raiding regularly and loot is starting to rain in, then its usually time to move to some sort of points system.  As a guild becomes successful they get more and more applicants and people will begin to ask for more visibility and accountability of loot distribution than is typically available in officer assigned guilds.  <br>
<br>
When you have 50+ active raiders raiding several times a week it is very difficult for a small group of people (officers) to be fully aware of everyones contribution, so a points system means that everyone can see that they are getting recognition for the effort they put in, (they're earning points) and they know that they have control over their upgrades as opposed to relying on an officer / class senior to know which upgrade will be most suited to them.<br>
<br>
There are exceptions to every rule, and I'm sure there are players out there who can handle officer assigned loot for huge guilds and manage to be fair and make intelligent loot decissions, but from my experience there will be times when each loot system will be most appropriate for a guild and the hard part is recognising when its time to change. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-family:verdana;font-size:xx-small;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=50585" target="top">Eoden</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Half Elven Warlord<br>
